defaultWitness: 
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson DBEdefault,
default gave evidence.  
defaultQ1 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default  Good morning.  This is a special session of the Select Committee, to conduct a pre-appointment hearing of the Government’s preferred candidate for the Chairman of 
defaultOfcom
default, Dame Patricia Hodgson.  If I could start, Dame Patricia, what do you think are the main priorities you will face as the new Chairman of 
defaultOfcom
default?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default The communications sector in this country has been clearly a great success over the last decade.  It has been growing at twice the rate of the economy as a whole, there is a wider range of services, and on average prices have been falling in telecoms; they have come down for 10 years.  Clearly, this is because of technological innovation—the blossoming of our creative industries.  However, 
defaultOfcom
default has been doing some things right: an emphasis on competition, and rolling back regulation in telecoms, broadcasting and post.  The challenge for an incoming Chair is to sustain this direction of travel in a maturing market, which is very much easier said than done.  
defaultMy focus would be on continued growth, on choice, cost and quality for citizens and consumers, and achieved wherever possible through three priorities.  The first is competition between platforms.  If you think of the enormous success of 
defaultsmartphones
default and tablets, this requires the freeing up of spectrum and its more intensive use, so that the mobile companies, as they roll out 4G to 99%, can really offer superfast broadband and can complement fixed fibre, but give it a run for its money on cost and speed.  
defaultThe second priority is competition not just between platforms but within networks and platforms where they have market power.  I would hope 
defaultOfcom
default will focus on two ends of the supply chain: making sure that service and content providers can get fair and reasonable access to dominant networks and platforms, and at the demand end that consumers really 
defaulthave good information about quality and cost and can switch easily, and then roll back regulation in between where possible.  
defaultOf course, thirdly, there are areas where competition will not do it for consumers, and my priority will be for 
defaultOfcom
default to be speedy and effective in those areas.  One codicil: the technology means that everyone increasingly must have access to broadband as well as to phones, post and broadcasting, in which we have been used to universal access.  I regard this as particularly important, and extra important is the power that 
defaultOfcom
default has to mandate help for the vulnerable and disadvantaged with new technology.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ2 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Thank you.  We are going to want to come back to quite a few of those areas in perhaps a little more detail, but, before we do, you will be the first Chairman who is not trained as an economist, and 
defaultOfcom
default is an economic regulator essentially.  Do you think that is a disadvantage?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default I have spent quite a few years with the competition authorities: first of all the Mergers and Monopolies Commission, then the Competition Commission.  I have served on a wide range of panels to do with price determinations, abuse of a dominant position, mergers and so on.  I have undoubtedly brought a layman’s perspective to that, but I have both learned a great deal and found the ability to ask the possibly stupid question is an extraordinary advantage.  Those years of experience and the way they have informed obviously my career experience in the sector will be an advantage.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ3 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Select Committees have specialised in asking the obviously stupid question and have found it equally effective.  Can you just set out for us your other professional activities, both those you may have felt necessary to give up in order to take on this role and also which ones continue—which ones you intend to go on doing whilst also serving as Chairman?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default Yes, I finished as Principal of 
defaultNewnham
default last year, and since then I have been doing the Deputy Chair of 
defaultOfcom
default, and chairing the School Teachers’ Review Body on pay, which has been pretty demanding because there has been a total review of the teachers’ remuneration terms and conditions package.  We are completing our second report at Christmas and that will be the end of that heavy work; thereafter there will be a 1% referral from the Treasury, but that is less than a day a week.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ4 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Do you have any other commitments?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default Not at the moment, no.  I can obviously give the undertaking that 
defaultOfcom
default will be my main and overwhelming commitment if I am confirmed.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ5 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Thank you.  The term of this appointment has been reduced from five to three years.  Did they tell you why that was the case?  Do you think it is sensible to reduce it to what is quite a brief tenure?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default I do not know why they have done so and my speculations have not hit upon an explanation.  I of course have been Deputy Chair for a couple of years, and I have the advantage, if I am confirmed, that I would hit the ground running.  I am in the middle, as it were, of some priorities that I would have the opportunity to put fresh force 
defaultbehind.  I do think that in principle the terms for chairs of independent regulators should be of a decent period in order to reinforce their independence, and I think that is an important principle.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ6 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Following on from that, you will be aware that Colette Bowe, who gave evidence to us a few months ago, said one of the reasons she decided not to seek a second term was she was concerned that somebody in a position of wanting a second term might be vulnerable to political pressure from the Government of the day.  Do you agree with that and do you therefore agree with her that it should be a one-term appointment?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default I do agree with that, and that is certainly my current intention.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ7 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default It is your intention to serve only one term?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default That is my current intention. You never know what the precise circumstances are, but I believe that is right.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ8 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default Can I just ask, coming from the outside, what you think that 
defaultOfcom
default has done particularly well in carrying out its duties in the past, and what has it not done so well?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default The key decision that it made in its early days was functional separation of BT’s network from its retail operation.  That was the absolute key to competition for consumers and to the price falls that we have seen ever since.  The principle of that separation was taken forward with virtual unbundling of local access for broadband, which carried that on and was very well done.  
defaultOne of the frustrations of recent years, which I know I share with 
defaultOfcom
default colleagues, is sometimes the difficulty of not being able to bring in measures that bring redress for consumers fast enough.  This is to do with the litigation culture in this country.  Of course, appeals must be available if regulators get it wrong, but 
defaultOfcom
default has a particular problem, unlike some other regulators, in that its decisions can be appealed totally.  This has caused slowdowns in some of the things that it is pushed to do, and indeed the need to be even more technically precise on every issue that it embarks on.  The Government has accepted that this is a problem and there is a consultation from BIS as we speak, which may lead to improvements that will enable 
defaultOfcom
default to speed things up.  I do think it is a priority.  
defaultTracey Crouch:default That is something you feel very strongly about personally and you wish to see change in the future?  
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default Yes
default&#xa0;
defaultQ9 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default 
defaultOfcom’s
default responsibilities have obviously expanded since its establishment, and they will continue to do so no doubt.  How would you prioritise 
defaultOfcom’s
default work in respect of the consumer and promoting competition in the areas it regulates?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default Promoting competition in the area it regulates is its prime duty not only under the Act but because of the benefit it brings to consumers.  
defaultOfcom
default has done a very good job for consumers, and if you ever have time to go to its website, you will find it is an 
defaultabsolute cornucopia of really good advice, as well as data, that allows and helps the consumer to make good consumer decisions.  We could probably make more of that, and one of the things we need to look to is how to make people more aware of where they can get help and advice.  
defaultOfcom
default is not an ombudsman, so it is not the natural port of call for the consumer, and we need to make more of what we can do.  
defaultTracey Crouch:default We found, in particular in our recent inquiry into nuisance calls, that there is
default 
defaultquite often a misunderstanding from the consumer about how much 
defaultOfcom
default can do.  I commend our report to you when you have a moment to read it.  
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default I have read it; it is very good.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ10 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default With that in mind, how do you think that 
defaultOfcom
default should decide when and where it is appropriate to intervene to promote competition rather than by other means?  
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default There is a proper competition law process by which it assesses whether or not an organisation or service has significant market power, and, if it does, what the approach is—whether within the Competition Act it can exercise its ex ante powers, as it did with functional separation in BT, or whether it is an ex post competition decision, or a referral to the Competition Commission.  It will in a very proper process go through those formulations, according to what the issue is.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ11 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default However, the world is changing and obviously new technologies are being introduced, and sometimes, as we found with nuisance calls, the original intention of the regulator has not necessarily kept up with technological advancements.  Do you feel this is something you will challenge in terms of thinking that 
defaultOfcom
default should be dealing with this—that this is appropriate for 
defaultOfcom
default?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default Absolutely.  There is a structure of pretty well permanent review, which is very heavy in resource terms.  That is determined by the EU framework, so there is a rolling program of three-year reviews of each part of the market.  However, of course, if there are consumer problems—if there is obviously public concern or a complaint—then 
defaultOfcom
default will look at that specifically and outside its regular process of monitoring.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ12 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default One thing that is always under review is the budget, and we know that 
defaultOfcom
default has a declining budget.  What impact do you think this will have on its ability to achieve its objectives in its annual plan and complete its other statutory functions?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default As you probably know, the budget was cut by 28% in the first spending review, and there will be another 5% before 2016.  That is one third out of its costs.  
defaultOfcom
default took the decision to front load the cuts, and did so with a reduction in staff, overall salary bills, reduction in premises, and a review of its processes.  It also has the advantage of the review of the regulators in general and of what value it can get from closer co-operation across the regulatory landscape.  It is certainly tight.  I observe the staff working extremely hard.  It does have to be watched, but we are confident that the quality has been retained.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ13 default&#xa0; 
defaultTracey Crouch:default The budget has been cut, yet you are being asked to do more.  Do you think you are going to be able to go back to the Treasury and fight for 
defaultOfcom
default and try to make sure you protect the service going forward?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default We have accepted the spending review targets and we intend to deliver to them.  Clearly, if there were a particular additional duty, we would have to negotiate for the funding of that duty.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ14 default&#xa0; 
defaultJim Sheridan:default As I understand it, you will be on a fixed-term contract for three years, with a net of somewhere in the region of £500,000.  Is it £500,000 over three years—something like that?
defaultDame Patricia Hodgson:default I believe the Minister has set the remuneration at £142,500 per annum.
